2_1J3rJ8ecnwH2EPYa6MrgZttBNc61ACFiCj.body:
Do you mean that I now can post things in Zeronet as well? OMG!

Let me say this: Zeroid.bit is *broken*. One cannot feasibly authenticate there. Firefox on Linux here and CPUs go up to 100% and the GUI looks like it froze. Actually what happens is that there's a lot of computation going on, but it works (although slow as hell). 

Do you really have to rely so much on Javascript just to get around in Zeronet? Kind of sucks for those with modest specs.

> [nofish](#comment_123_1J3rJ8ecnwH2EPYa6MrgZttBNc61ACFiCj): Probably your browser does not support webgl properly, so it falls back to software rendering. Can you please check your value of "Major Performance Caveat" on https://www.browserleaks.com/webgl page?
> Edit: Added performance monitoring to ZeroID and disabling the animation if necessary

Sure, I see why now, but the question is: why force the use of WebGL for the creation of a *certificate*? I already dislike that ZeroNet has to rely so much on Javascript alone, and to me that's just putting another big hurdle around the usability of the software.

Major Performance Caveat returns `no` for me, but it tells me that WebGL 2.0 isn't supported (1.0 is fine).

1_14tZUZypdydwcKr3KwVng6XY85YJynBNrk.body:
I've seen a few sites that try to fill in on this role, but none of them are any close to being complete indexes of the network. There's no "Google" around here as far as I know.

I know of these:

 - [ZeroName](http://127.0.0.1:43110/1Name2NXVi1RDPDgf5617UoW7xA6YrhM9F) - lists addresses that have been registered in NameCoin, but leaves out the many remaining sites that haven't yet.
 - [ZeroSearch](http://127.0.0.1:43110/zerosearch.bit) - allows you to search an index of 141 sites with keywords, or add your own to the list. Unfortunately, the process is manual, and not everyone does it anyway.

A few other sites named "Zeronet Index" or similar exist, but in my opinion none of them are any close to being as resourceful as the two above, and that's not to say that they're any close to complete either.

If anyone else has a better index please share it with us!

Also, if you look around the posts here in ZeroTalk you can find a few unlisted sites. [This thread](http://127.0.0.1:43110/Talk.ZeroNetwork.bit/?Topic:3_168qV1Xxp2EyszrzdECLUwXrn9wGYjDdar/NEW+WEBSITE+share+it+here) should be particularly interesting to you.

15_1PvAyLAB5H1JKbiFjx95ZJXrNJVyWxs5Hf.body:
You can talk about all these "deep web" services like Tor's `.onion` hidden sites, I2P and Freenet, but in my opinion none of them quite come close to the truly P2P experience that ZeroNet does. When you think about it, none of the above work when your connection goes down, or if the owner of a given site decides to take it offline, whereas ZeroNet remains available (although stale). Hence, under that strict definition, I don't think that there is any real alternative to ZeroNet nowadays. You could mention IPFS and it's similarly structured P2P nature for datastore, but ZeroNet is also dynamic, whereas IPFS is almost static.

Don't get me wrong here, I love and use every single service mentioned in this post, but when I think about resilience and resistance to censorship, I don't think any of them is as advanced as ZeroNet, and now with Tor support it's as advanced as ever.

I think we should focus now on the other side of the equation: the connection. All solutions rely on internet connection, which can be shut down by telcos. Hyperboria and other meshnets are a good starting point in my opinion. It's like P2P internet.

> [ekaterina](#comment_44_1Mk5sVKeCrwMc3wSD11jM7DZTiqF5D9BaD): IPFS does plan to support dynamic websites through IPNS, their nameservice. Basically (as I understand it, so I might be incorrect), you can create a name that points to a resource, lets say the JSON file data.json which is used as a database in ZeroNet. 
> To make it dynamic, this same name using IPNS can be used to point to the hash of the new, changed data.json file, so when I request the resource behind the name data.json I will always receive the newest version of the data.json file, with new comments added, new votes, whatever it is that is stored in there.

Interesting, didn't think about it. Had forgotten about IPNS for a second. This sounds like an interesting application!

1_1Gb4DzrdjGBCiTnVyZRB2CHfdSnBfb4FY1.body:
> [ulrichard](#comment_14_1PSaHi14Xh4Kjo3yyjDgbRtj4YLQgWV4QJ): When you delete a zite in ZeroHello, it should be gone, right?

Yes, but remember that while a simple "delete" command (like `rm` in Linux) makes it hard for an average user to recover a file, a forensics expert with plenty of experience can still recover it from the filesystem. Full disk encryption is still your best bet, but if you can't have it, then at least use something like `shred -u FILENAME` to "securely" delete your file.
